{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>Spectrins are involved in the support of general membrane integrity, stabilisation of cell-cell interactions, axonal growth, normal functioning of the Golgi complex and organisation of synaptic vesicles [[cite:PUB00035923], [cite:PUB00035924], [cite:PUB00035925]]. Spectrin is a tetrameric actin cross-linking protein, which contains two alpha and two beta subunits. Two genes for alpha-spectrin [[cite:PUB00035926], [cite:PUB00035927], [cite:PUB00035925]] and five for beta-spectrin have been identified in both mice and humans, each of which is alternatively spliced to produce multiple spectrin isoforms [[cite:PUB00035928], [cite:PUB00035926]]. Beta-spectrins are more diverse than alpha-spectrin, and include mammalian erythrocytic beta-spectrin, non-erythroid beta-spectrin/Fodrin (beta-G, the general form of beta-spectrin expressed in multiple tissues), a novel beta-G spectrin (ELF1-4) that lacks the C-terminal PH (pleckstrin homology) domain, the brain-specific SPTBN2, and beta-V spectrin.</p>\n\n<p>ELF ([swissprot:Q62261]), a modulator of the Smad adaptor proteins involved in the TGF-beta signalling pathway, was originally identified from endodermal stem/progenitor cells committed to foregut lineage [[cite:PUB00035929], [cite:PUB00024191]]. ELF is a beta-spectrin that is important for distinct functional membrane generation, protein sorting, cell adhesion and the development of a polarized differentiated epithelial cell [[cite:PUB00035924], [cite:PUB00035930]]. ELF-deficient mice display disruption of transforming growth factor-beta (TGF-beta) signalling by Smad proteins [[cite:PUB00035929]]. Evidence from null mutants of ELF confirms that ELF is a novel beta-G spectrin and not an isoform of beta-spectrins [[cite:PUB00035925]]. Aberrations in Elf's involvement in Smad4 localization and subsequent activation of Smad4 could result in tumourigenesis.</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :repr